Smart approach. Here's the prompt to pass your screenshot to a vision model (GPT-4o, Gemini, or Claude) to get a structured text description your agent can consume:

---

```
You are a UI layout analyst. I will give you a screenshot of a webpage section.
Your job is to describe it in structured JSON that a front-end AI agent will use 
to reconstruct the UI in React/TSX. Be precise and technical — this output 
replaces the screenshot entirely, so nothing visual should be left ambiguous.

Analyze the screenshot and return ONLY a JSON object with this exact structure 
(no markdown, no explanation, just raw JSON):

{
  "section": "<navbar|hero|cards|form|footer|sidebar|modal|other>",
  "layout": {
    "type": "<flex|grid|absolute|stack>",
    "direction": "<row|column>",
    "columns": <number or null>,
    "gap": "<estimated gap in px>",
    "alignment": "<start|center|end|space-between|space-around>",
    "verticalAlignment": "<start|center|end>",
    "padding": "<estimated padding e.g. '16px 24px'>",
    "maxWidth": "<estimated max width or 'full'>",
    "isSticky": <true|false>,
    "isFullWidth": <true|false>
  },
  "background": {
    "color": "<hex or rgba>",
    "hasImage": <true|false>,
    "hasGradient": <true|false>,
    "gradientDescription": "<describe if present, else null>",
    "opacity": <0-1>
  },
  "elements": [
    {
      "id": "<short unique name e.g. 'logo', 'nav-links', 'cta-button'>",
      "type": "<text|image|button|input|icon|divider|badge|card|list|link|avatar>",
      "position": "<left|center|right|absolute — relative to parent>",
      "content": "<actual text content if visible, else null>",
      "style": {
        "fontSize": "<estimated px>",
        "fontWeight": "<400|500|600|700>",
        "color": "<hex or rgba>",
        "backgroundColor": "<hex or rgba or null>",
        "borderRadius": "<px or null>",
        "border": "<describe or null>",
        "padding": "<px values or null>",
        "width": "<px or % or 'auto'>",
        "height": "<px or 'auto'>",
        "shadow": "<describe or null>",
        "opacity": <0-1>
      },
      "states": {
        "hasHoverEffect": <true|false>,
        "isActive": <true|false>,
        "isDisabled": <true|false>
      },
      "children": []
    }
  ],
  "responsiveness": {
    "observedBreakpoint": "<mobile|tablet|desktop>",
    "notes": "<any responsive behavior you can infer>"
  },
  "spacing": {
    "betweenElements": "<estimated px>",
    "sectionPaddingTop": "<px>",
    "sectionPaddingBottom": "<px>"
  },
  "typography": {
    "dominantFont": "<font name if identifiable, else null>",
    "headingSize": "<px or null>",
    "bodySize": "<px or null>",
    "lineHeight": "<estimated or null>"
  },
  "notes": "<anything unusual, overlapping elements, animations, z-index stacking, patterns that don't fit the schema>"
}

Rules:
- Estimate pixel values by comparing elements to each other — e.g. if the font 
  looks like standard body text assume 16px, headings 24-32px etc.
- For colors, give your best hex estimate from what you see. 
  Prefer exact over vague (say '#1E293B' not 'dark navy').
- Nest children inside parent elements using the "children" array.
- If a section has repeating items (cards, list rows, nav links), describe ONE 
  instance fully and add "repeats": <count> to that element.
- Do not describe anything outside the screenshot boundary.
- Do not add commentary outside the JSON object.
```

---

**How to use this in your pipeline:**

```
screenshot  ──►  vision model + above prompt  ──►  layout-description.json
                                                            │
                               ┌────────────────────────────┘
                               ▼
              agent receives:  ui-spec.json  +  layout-description.json
                               │
                               ▼
                        builds React component
```

Your agent prompt then becomes:

```
You are a React/TSX UI builder.

You have two inputs:

1. ui-spec.json — contains exact design tokens (colors, fonts, spacing, 
   border radius, shadows) extracted programmatically from the target site.

2. layout-description.json — contains a structured visual description of 
   one UI section, produced by analyzing a screenshot.

Your job:
- Build a single React TSX component for the section described in 
  layout-description.json
- Use ONLY token values from ui-spec.json for all colors, font sizes, 
  spacing, and border radius — never invent design values
- If layout-description.json gives a color that conflicts with ui-spec.json, 
  prefer ui-spec.json (it is ground truth from computed styles)
- Use Tailwind CSS with the custom token classes already configured
- Make the component match the layout structure exactly: respect column counts,
  flex direction, gap, padding, and element positions
- For repeating elements (cards, list rows) use .map() with sample data
- Export the component as default

ui-spec.json:
<paste here>

layout-description.json:
<paste here>
```

This keeps your agent fully text-based while the vision model handles all the visual interpretation — clean separation of concerns.
